{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_dowe_ver01/data/sn92073229/00332891868/1958040301/0260.xml":{"full_text":"Page Two\nThe Chapel Hill Weekly\nChapel HiH North Carolina\nUS B. Ihihiti Tetepfca mt S-1271 or MSI\nPvWhdMd Every Moaday and Tbnraday\nBy The Chapel Hill PoblnUnnr Caaepany. lat\nLoris Gravks Camtr Uniting Editor\nJot Jones Managing Editor\nOr.T-Ut Caripbeli Coirti Monape*\nJamzs E Ckjtckd. Acvrrtiting Manage*\nCtUMLTOK Camiwcu. Mechanical Sup:.\nMltmml aa \u2014rrmfl rl\u00abo matter February S IMS, at\ntte poet office at Cnape: HU. Nomt Carolina unoar\nthe art of Martfc ItTt\nSt BSCEimON RATES\nId Omnge County, Year fAOC\n<6 mcmtfc t ZJ2S. 8 month*. $1.60)\nOutside of Oran gt County by the Year\nStates of K. C\u201e Va., and 6 C. ASO\nOther State* and Dirt of Columbia \u00a3-00\nCanada. Mexico, South America '-0C\nEurope *.M>\nThe Improvement of Administration\nof Justice in North Carolina\nA special issue of Popular Govern\nment the magazine published by the\nInstitute of Government, is devoted to\na report of the North Carolina State\nBar Association\u2019s Committee on Im\nproving the Administration of Justice\nin North Carolina.\nThe main body of the report, made up\nof s review and proposals entitled \u201cThe\nCourts of Yesterday, Today and Tomor\nrow in North Carolina,\" was written by\nAlbert Coates, director of the Institute,\nwith the assistance of his present col\nleagues, Alex Biggs and Robert Mid\ngette; his former colleagues, Clifton\nBumgarner, BasH Sherrill and I>illard\nGardner; and Gladys Hall Coates. The\nintroduction is a letter from J. Spencer\nBell of Charlotte, chairman of the com\nmittee, addressed \u2018To the Lawyers of\nNorth Carolina.\"\nMr. Coatee and his associate* have\nbeen working for many months on his\ntorical research, interviewing, and writ\ning for the committee. It has been a\ntremendous task and for it they deserve\nthe gratitude of the State.\nI am particularly interested in this\npassage in Mr. Bell's letter to the law\nyers: \u201cYour committee is not working\nto produce a comprehensive and scho\nlarly report to gather dust upon the\nshelves of research libraries. We are,\nrather, trying to produce a comprehen\nsive and accurate report for a very\npractical purpose\u2014improving and ex\npediting the administration of justice\nin North Carolina. To achieve this end\nwe must start with accurate informa\ntion and apply that information to ar\nrive at a recommendation which will be\nboth sound in principle and acceptable\nin fact to the people of North Carolina.\nWe need your help at each stage of the\ntask.\"\n\u201cWe need your help.\nMr. Bell, you said it!\nMy particular interest in Mr. Bell\u2019s\nremarks here quoted is based upon the\nfact that previous proposals for the im\nprovement of the administration of jus\ntice in North Carolina have been killed\nby the legal profession itself. When I\nsay \u201cthe fact\u201d 1 am not supposing. I\nam speaking from the best of testi\nmony. In the course of the years mem\nbers of committees (or they may have\nbeen called commissions) appointed by\nthe Legislature to study the judicial\nsystem and the codes and the rules of\npractice, and to recommend improve\nments, have told me of how they would\nreceive handsome compliments upon\nthe reports they presented\u2014and then\nsee the reports pigeonholed or killed by\nlawyers who did not like this or that\nfeature of them.\nReforms in the administration of jus\ntice thus far have been supported by\nthe better element of lawyers among\nthe members but not by an element\nlarge enough to put them through. I\nhope the degree of cooperation received\nin the Legislature by the advocates of\na reform of the justice of the peace sys\ntem is not a measure of the cooperation\nthat Mr, Bell\u2019s committee will receive.\nAnd my forecast is that it will not\nturn out to be. The present effort at\nimprovement of the administration of\njustice in the State is more thorough\nand determined than one has ever been\nbefore. And I believe the next Legis\nlature will be more receptive to propos\nals for reform than past Legislatures\nhave been. The problem of Mr. Bell\nand Mr. Coates is largely one of public\nrelations, which embraces appeals to\npublic opinion as well as contacts with\nmembers of the Legislature. And a\npmMetn of public relations is one that\nMr. Bell and Mr. Coates know how to\nhandle -4*o.\n\nAlfred S. Lawrence\nThe Reverend Alfred Stratton Law\nrence, who was rector of the Episcopal\nchurch here for 22 years and rector\nemeritus for 15 years, died last Friday\nwhen he was 18 days short of 76 years\nold.\nWhen I think of Mr. Lawrence 1\nthink of a man in whom devoutness,\nbroadmindedness, and interest in the\naffairs of the world around him were\ncombined to a remarkable degree. His\nfriendliness and his understanding na\nture made him an ideal pastor for a\ncollege community like Chapel Hill. On\none day he would be talking to a com\npany of students in the church or par\nish house, and on the next day he would\nbe acting as chief referee of a track\nmeet on the campus. He was well quali\nfied for companionship with youth be\ncause he had been a track star himself.\nHe was bora in Essex, England, April\n15, 1882. came to the United States\nwhen he was a boy, and was graduated\nfrom Columbia University in 1905. He\nreceived his bachelor of divinity degree\nfrom the General Theological Semina\nry\nHe was a chaplain in the First World\nWar and I remember seeing him often\nat American Legion memorial cere\nmonies. His activities in the Legion\npost here led to many friendships and\nhe enjoyed an exceptional popularity\namong members of all denominations.\nHis tolerance, his gentleness, and his\nwarm sympathies made him a truly\nlovable man.\u2014L.G.\n*>de to Lirpa\n'Charlotte Levin in HSA Life)\nApril is the month when it isn\u2019t rain\ning rain, you know, it\u2019s raining violets.\nApril\u2019s in Paris, too. And April Fool\u2019s\nDay is ill April this year.\nLirpa is April spelled backwards.\nApril\u2019s also the tiro# when flow ere\nare in bloom and everyone in love\nmakes a blovraing idiot of himself.\nApril's th\u00a7 time when women change\nfrom tight sweaters to sack dresses.\nApril's the fourth month of the year,\ncontaining 80 days, with time off for\ngood behavior.\nApril 24 is the last day a Ph.D. can\ndidate can file his dissertation.\nDid you know that the victims of the\nriotous festivities on April first are\nknown in France as April fish (poisson\nd\u2019Avril), in Scotland as a howk or cuc\nkoo, and in our ow-n dear English\nspeaking country as a fool?\nAnd remember, it isn\u2019t raining rain,\nyou know, it\u2019s raining II two 0.\nParsnip Quilting\n'The FraakUa PreMl\nWomen are the weaker sex\u2014delicate\ncreatures who recoil from anything the\nleast bit offensive. That\u2019s what we\u2019ve\nalways been told. But it just isn\u2019t so!\nIt isn\u2019.t, at least, where food is concern\ned.\nProof that it isn\u2019t comas from Mrs.\nEd Crawford. In her news report last\nweek from the Ridgecrest-Watauga\nsection, she tells of an annual affair\nthe women of that community have\nbeen holding for six years. They get\ntogether once a year, ostensibly to\nquilt, but actually to eat parsnipe. At\nthe latest conclave thirteen women\nsmacked their lips over parsnips.\nMrs. Crawford explains, \u201cFew, if\nany, men of the community care for\nparsnip*.\u2019\u2019 That remark we\u2019d classify\nas the understatement of the year.\nThe Year I Was Twenty-On*\n(Corltoe kUni* la GateovlUe Index)\nPeople sometimes tell me my writing\nis sad and that I must have had a lone\nly life. They ask me to write humorous\npieces for my column more often. 1 be\nlieve the influence of the depression\nyears made a lasting impression on me\nthat I will never be able to forget.\n1 remember the year my dad was\nbuilding a big home for a lumber man\nin our community. My dad was a first\nclass mechanic and was drawing top\npay of 25 cents per hour. We had an\nold mule and I undertook to farm our\nlittle place as well as another farm\nabout five miles away. In the spring\nand summer I arose at 4 a m. and drove\nthe mule the five miles and worked all\nday and drove back home. He died the\nweek after the crop was laid by. Papa\nalways said I plowed him to death.\nOne day Papa jumped on me about\nmy appearance. All summer I had fol\nlowed the old mule with only a pair of\nragged dungarees for adornment, and\nhe felt I was Indecent since I had torn\nthe pants off above the knees and wore\nno shoes. He turned quickly away from\nme when I told him I had no other work\nclothes, and I guess his heart broke Just\nTHE CHAPEL HILL WEEKLY\n\u201cHmmm\u2014l Wonder For Whom Th\u2019 Bell Will Tol]?\u201d\nNow and Then By Bill Prouty\nEverybody, it seems, has a remedy\nfor the recession. The Democrats blame\nthe Republicans for the sag, and would\ncure it one way, while the Republicans,\nwho, of course, must be different, blame\nthe J>emocrats, and would use another\nmethod.\nThe President has idga about\nhow it should be handled, while the\nCongress has yet another plan.\nLabor says it\u2019s management\u2019s fault,\nwhile the owners claim that labor's de\nmand for more and more pay is respon\nsible for the spiraling prices.\nThe white-collar man also has his\nown ideas. But being unorganized, his\nvoice is like the goldfish\u2019s-\u2014bis ample\nmouth is always open and wagging, but\nnobody of any consequence ever hears\nwhat he\u2019s saying.\nEverybody, then, has a different idea\nabout how to cure the recession; but\nabove the cacophony of discordant ideas\nthere can be heard a persistent theme:\n\u201creduce taxes, reduce taxes, reduce\ntaxes!\u201d\nNow, this being an election year,\nhere iB something both I>emocrats and\nRepublicans can agree upon. And it has\nbeen rumored that more than just a\nfew eligible vote-casters are not exact\nly repulsed by this rather quaint idea\nthat you can slow down an inflationary\ntrend by giving the buyers more money\nto spend.\nWalter Winchell, for one, thinks it\u2019s\na good idea; but then it\u2019s quite possible\nthat most huge salary earners feel the\nsame way about it.\nNot everybody agrees with the idea\nthough. Take Barney Baruch. He says\nit\u2019s folly to reduce taxes in order to\nease the squeeze. He\u2019s for a freeze on\nwages and prices alike and for a\nstrenthening of the government\u2019s cred\nit. Thi\u00df would mean no tax reductions.\nAnd it\u2019s quite probable that this\ngreat old \u201cadviser to presidents\u201d is\nexactly right. After all, when a man of\na little too for that week he dipped into\nhis meagre earnings to buy me some\nshoes and work clothes. That was the\nyear I was twenty-one.\nMy story should have a happy end\ning, but there is little laughter in a de\npression. A hurricane swept down on\nthe coast just aa my bean crop was in\nbloom and I sold the entire summer\u2019s\nwork for S3O. How can a man forget\na time like that?\nSarah Grand: Just do a thing and\ndon\u2019t talk about it. This is the great\nsecret of success in all enterprises.\nDavid Lloyd George: There is noth\ning so fatal to character aa half fin\nished\nBaruch\u2019s business acumen makes a\nstatement about fiscal matters, there\nare many who will listen.\nOn the other hand, there must be ma\nny who would ask what Barney knows\nabout income taxes. Didn\u2019t he make\nmost of his fortune before there was an\nincome tax? And besides, they know\nBarney doesn\u2019t have much income\nnow\u2014he\u2019s got it all already, hasn\u2019t he?\nIs there, then, a solution to this di\nlemma?\nYes. All you've got to do is to con\nvince everybody, or most of the peo\nple, anyway, that there is no recession,\nand you\u2019ll have the problem licked. No\nrecession, no problem it\u2019s as simple\nas that.\nBut how are you going to do this?\nJust remind the people that only 25\nyears ago this country was going\nthrough the greatest depression of its\nshort but wonderful history. Remind\nthem of the bread lines, the soup kitch\nens, the flophouses. Tell thorn again\nabout apple and pencil sellers; the\nhaunted look on the faces of the job\nless, the hungry and the destitute.\nTake those who have forgotten or\nwere too young to remember, down by\nthe railroad tracks where the empty\nfreight cars squeal by carrying their\ncargoes of miserable human flotsam\ninto the dark unknown.\nTake them down to the banks to see\nthe hysterical women crying against\nthe closed doors, their savings wiped\nout. Go by the morgues for a last look\nat the broken bodies of those people,\nboth honest and dishonest, who couldn\u2019t\nface the consequences of the crash.\nTell them about the sharecroppers\u2019\nplight; acquaint them again with the\nbitter and open warfare between labor\nand the owners. Go out and take a look\nat the bonus marchers camped outside\nWashington, honest men reduced to\nbegging for bread.\nFollow a bxokendown load of Okie*,\nout from the void of the wind-blown\ndeserts to the forbidden borders of Cal\nifornia. Or go along a while with the\nwretched migrant workers, moving,\nmoving all the time, looking for food\nand shelter, but without hope of finding\nit\n\u201cA chicken in every pot,\u201d was the\nbest they were hoping for in those\ndays\u2014even the politicians. Why, most\npeople didn't even have a pot to cook\nin.\nRecession? Where\u2019s the recession?\nYou see, it isn\u2019t hard to eliminate if\nyou\u2019ll only look back a few years. And\nif the tightening up that\u2019s going on now\nwill scrape a little fat off our unbeliev\nably easy-living lives, then these days\nmay go down as a period of \u201cproces\nsion\u201d rather than \u201crecession,\u201d\nI Like Chapel Hill\nBy Billy Arthur\nThe characters in the Coffee Club or the Coffee\nClub characters, have it whichever you wish, chided me\npleasantly and lambasted me seriously for a gross error\nin this space last week.\nI erred when I tied Mr. Robert Lester to the Ford\nFoundation. It\u2019s the Rockefeller money\u2014and I don\u2019t\nmean dimes\u2014that he passes out to deserving people.\nI only got my men mixed, because\nLives of millionaires all remind us\nThat we've got to own the stock,\nIf we want to leave behind us\nEndowments on every block.\nfc**\nA new champion has been elected in the Coffee\nClub. Boxer Mike Ronman, on his first time out in\nseveral weeks, floored Frank West on Friday, March 28.\nMike paid for 18 cups, defeating West who had held the\ntitle for some time with 16 cups.\nt\nOn a recent afternoon I dropped into South Build\ning, planning to pay some respects to President Bill\nFriday.\nAnd I learned he doesn\u2019t live there any more.\n\u201cHe and Mr. Carmichael moved down to the new\noffices, the old Institute of Government building, about\na month ago,\u201d I was told, pleasantly. \u201cDidn\u2019t you know\nthat?\u201d\nI didn\u2019t.\nThen I was asked if I wouldn\u2019t settle for a look at\nChancellor Bill Aycock\u2019s office instead.\n1 would. And therein lies my little story.\nIt\u2019s: a comfortably attractive office, and fitted with\nhand-me-downs. Some University officials with long\nmemories had recalled pieces of furniture in storage\nhere and there about the campus and had done them up\nand over beautifully.\nThey know that the cabinet and the reception\nchairs belonged to the late and loved Horace Williams.\nThe chairs were in his dining room, and the cabinet is\nhis old china closet with the mirror removed. Some\nother pieces in the office were unidentified.\n\u201cWe scavenged here and there,\u201d I was told \u201cDon\u2019t\nyou think we\u2019ve done a good job? Isn\u2019t it pretty?\u201d\nIt is.\ni i\nOn the same afternoon I encountered Fid Lanier\nand offered to trade my vote for a cup of Book Fix cof\nfee. \u201cI\u2019ll bet it\u2019ll cost me more than that before the\nprimary\u2019s over,\u201d Fid wagered.\nI told him I had phoned several days earlier foi*\nsome information but he wasn\u2019t around. He apologized\nand wanted to know if he still could help. And that\nbrings me to this:\nI confessed that after I had slept on my question,\nI realized 1 didn\u2019t need the information after all, that it\nwas superfluous.\n\u201cI know, I know,\u201d Fid replied. \u201cThat\u2019s just like\nthe folks who call you up and the first thing they say\nis \u2018I just thought of something.\u2019 Nine times out of ten\nwhat they\u2019ve thought up and got to get off their chest\nright then doesn't amount to a hill of beans. If they\u2019d\nIx-en working at something as they should, they\nwouldn\u2019t have time to think of the inconsequential\nthings. I\u2019m always wary of those people who say \u2018I just\nthought of something.\u2019\n\nA pessimist is an optimist who discovered that\nthat wasn\u2019t a dummy whammy he just drove over.\nCHAPEL HILL CHAFF\n(Contiawd Irani Pag* I)\nAs we walked along, Mr. Lester pointed out to me\nthe variations in size, shape, and color, and now and\nthen we earn# upon a blossom that was yellow on the in\nside and white on the outside. Manuals and dictionaries\nwill tell you that the difference between the daffodil\nand the jonquil is that the daffodil has a long trumpet\n(called the corona) and the jonquil has a short one.\nThey\u2019re both members of the narcissus family and ma-\nny people don\u2019t notice the difference between them. I\ncall \u2019m both daffodils, partly because when I look at\nthem closely most of them seem to have long trumpets\nbut because daffodil is a prettier name than jonquil.\nAs you go around Chapel Hill you see that there\nare two ways of displaying daffodils. One is to scatter\nthem over a lawn as Mrs. Noel Houston has done in\nGreenwood and one as Mrs. James Street did in Green\nwood on the place in Westwood where Mr. and Mrs. J.\nL. Conners now live. In the other way they are bor\nders for lawns, paths, pools, and rockbound circles of\ngrass, as on the Lester and the Kyser places and many\nothers.\nThe trouble I always run into when I write about\ndaffodils or any other flowers in Chape) Hill is that it\u2019s\nnot possible to name but a few of the gardens and yards\nwhere there are beautiful sights. One stretch that\ncharms me year after year is the charming little pink 1\nflowers, that I can never remember the name of, cling-\ning to the Vic Huggins wall on West University Drive.\nThere are hundreds of gardeners in the village whose\ngreen thumbs have produced not only green but also\nwhite and pink and lavender and scarlet and golden. I\nwish I could name all these artists who, by touching a\ntimely spur and saying a few persuasive words to na\nture, have triumphed over the evil weather. If they\nput wraps on and go out to brave a surly winter that\nstays on and on, those of us who leave them the work\nto do ought to account it a privilege to ride snugly up\nand down the streets and roads as spectators.\nBUFFET EVERY SUNDAY S:SO4tM\nThursday, April 3, 1958","height":"26493","width":"19850"}}
